@* LINQ over a List (BENCH n°35, decision 116): `_nums.Where(x => x > 0).Count()` compiles to
   `_nums.filter(x => x > 0).length` -- the common LINQ operators map to JS array methods (Where -> filter,
   Select -> map, Count -> length, Any -> some, …). The source List is already a materialised JS array, so the
   eager array methods are faithful to a LINQ chain ending in a scalar, and the predicate lambda translates
   through the same machinery as the rest of @code. #go counts the positives in [-2, 3, -1, 5, 0] -- so #value
   goes "0" -> "2", exactly as Blazor runs the same C# LINQ. No runtime primitive is added: it is pure array
   methods. count is read by @count AND assigned by Go -> a signal; _nums is never mutated -> a plain array. *@

<p>Positives: <span id="value">@count</span></p>

<button id="go" @onclick="Go">go</button>

@code {
    private int count = 0;
    private System.Collections.Generic.List<int> _nums = new System.Collections.Generic.List<int> { -2, 3, -1, 5, 0 };

    private void Go()
    {
        count = _nums.Where(x => x > 0).Count();
    }
}
